   <body class="- topic/body " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\hotplug\sar_synep_request.xml" xtrc="body:1;17:24">
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\hotplug\sar_synep_request.xml" xtrc="p:1;20:21">Surprise adding Endpoints into a running system may fail for the following reasons:</p>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\hotplug\sar_synep_request.xml" xtrc="p:2;23:21">1. The BIOS has not allocated sufficient MMIO resources for the new device</p>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\hotplug\sar_synep_request.xml" xtrc="p:3;26:21">2. The BIOS has not allocated PCIe bus resources for the new device</p>
      <p class="- topic/p " xtrf="C:\Git\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\XDocs-DITA-OT-185\DITA-OT1.8.5\samples\diffed\_b-0-file-\Trident\device\devspec\hotplug\sar_synep_request.xml" xtrc="p:4;29:21">In modern hot-plug capable hosts, the BIOS will generally pre-allocate a "token" amount of MMIO for all slots in the system. For NVMe, only a "token" amount of MMIO (normally 1-2MB) is required so NVMe EPs are generally supported out-of-box in modern hosts. However, other devices such as GPUs have much larger MMIO requirements (typically 2GB or more) which are generally not properly pre-allocated by the BIOS. In addition to this limitation, modern hosts may not pre-allocate PCIe bus numbers for a switch to be added to a single downstream root port.</p>
